<DocsLayout title="Shell Essentials" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Shell Essentials</h1>

  <p>
    The command line is your primary interface to the AIRLab servers. This guide covers
    everything from connecting for the first time to monitoring GPU usage and moving files
    around. If you are new to the Linux shell, work through this page before anything else.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-accent-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
    </svg>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Recommended reading:</strong> MIT's
      <a href="https://missing.csail.mit.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Missing Semester of Your CS Education</a>
      is an excellent, free course covering the shell, editors, Git, and more.
      It takes about a weekend to work through and will save you hours every week.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SSH ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="ssh">Connecting via SSH</h2>

  <p>
    SSH (Secure Shell) creates an encrypted connection to the remote server. Your
    co-supervisor will give you the server's IP address (<code>WESTWORLD_IP</code>).
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`ssh firstname.lastname@WESTWORLD_IP`}
  />

  <p>
    To avoid typing the IP and username every time, add an alias in your SSH client
    configuration file:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    filename="~/.ssh/config"
    code={`Host airlab
  HostName WESTWORLD_IP
  User firstname.lastname
  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_airlab   # see SSH Keys below
  ServerAliveInterval 60
  ServerAliveCountMax 3`}
  />

  <p>
    With this in place, you connect with just:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock lang="bash" filename="local machine" code={`ssh airlab`} />

  <!-- ── SSH Keys ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="ssh-keys">SSH Keys</h2>

  <p>
    Password authentication is convenient but weaker than key-based authentication.
    Set up an SSH key pair once and never type your password over the network again.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`# 1. Generate a key pair (Ed25519 is the modern standard)
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "airlab-$(date +%Y)" -f ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_airlab

# 2. Copy the public key to the server
ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_airlab.pub firstname.lastname@WESTWORLD_IP

# 3. Test key login (no password prompt means it worked)
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_airlab firstname.lastname@WESTWORLD_IP whoami`}
  />

  <!-- ── Navigation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="navigation">Navigation & File Operations</h2>

  <p>
    These are the commands you will use every day. Master them and the rest becomes
    much easier.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>pwd</code></td><td>Print current directory</td><td><code>pwd</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>ls</code></td><td>List directory contents</td><td><code>ls -lah</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>cd</code></td><td>Change directory</td><td><code>cd ~/datasets/private</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>mkdir</code></td><td>Create a directory</td><td><code>mkdir -p results/run_01</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>cp</code></td><td>Copy files or directories</td><td><code>cp -r src/ backup/</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>mv</code></td><td>Move or rename</td><td><code>mv old_name.py new_name.py</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>rm</code></td><td>Delete files</td><td><code>rm -rf results/old_run/</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>cat</code></td><td>Print file contents</td><td><code>cat config.yaml</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>less</code></td><td>Page through a file</td><td><code>less training.log</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>grep</code></td><td>Search inside files</td><td><code>grep "val_loss" training.log</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>find</code></td><td>Search for files</td><td><code>find . -name "*.pt"</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>du</code></td><td>Disk usage</td><td><code>du -sh ~/datasets/private/*</code></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-danger">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-red-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
      <line x1="15" y1="9" x2="9" y2="15"/><line x1="9" y1="9" x2="15" y2="15"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong><code>rm -rf</code> has no undo.</strong> On a shared server there is no
      trash bin and no backup for your home directory. Double-check the path before
      pressing Enter, every single time.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Useful patterns</h3>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# Search command history
history | grep docker

# Run the last command again as root (use sparingly)
sudo !!

# Background a running process (Ctrl+Z pauses, then:)
bg        # resume in background
jobs      # list background jobs
fg %1     # bring job 1 back to foreground

# Count lines in a file
wc -l training.log

# Sort and unique a list
cat labels.txt | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn

# Extract a .tar.gz archive into a specific directory
tar -xzf dataset.tar.gz -C ~/datasets/private/`}
  />

  <!-- ── Monitoring ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="monitoring">Monitoring Resources</h2>

  <p>
    Before starting an experiment, always check that the resources you booked are
    actually free.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# CPU, RAM, and per-process stats (interactive, press q to quit)
htop

# Full GPU status: memory usage, utilisation, running processes
nvidia-smi

# Compact GPU memory summary
nvidia-smi --query-gpu=index,name,memory.used,memory.free,memory.total \
           --format=csv,noheader,nounits

# Watch GPU utilisation live every 2 seconds
watch -n 2 nvidia-smi

# Check available disk space
df -h /home
df -h /data    # NAS mount point`}
  />

  <p>
    When using <code>htop</code>, press <kbd>F6</kbd> to sort by CPU or memory,
    <kbd>F5</kbd> to toggle tree view (see which processes belong to which parent),
    and <kbd>F9</kbd> to send a signal (e.g., to kill a stuck process).
  </p>

  <!-- ── File Transfer ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="transfer">Transferring Files</h2>

  <p>
    Use <code>scp</code> for quick one-off transfers and <code>rsync</code> for anything
    larger or incremental (it skips files that haven't changed).
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`# Copy a single file to the server
scp local_file.py airlab:~/project/

# Copy an entire directory to the server
scp -r ./results/ airlab:~/project/results/

# rsync a directory (faster for large transfers, skips unchanged files)
rsync -avz --progress ./dataset/ airlab:~/datasets/private/my_dataset/

# Download results from the server to your local machine
rsync -avz airlab:~/project/results/ ./local_results/`}
  />

  <!-- ── Getting Help ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="help">Getting Help</h2>

  <p>
    Every standard Unix command comes with built-in documentation. The most important
    ways to access it:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# Full manual page (press q to quit, / to search)
man rsync

# Short usage summary (works for most commands)
rsync --help

# Quick one-line description of any command
whatis find

# Search manual pages by keyword
apropos "compress"`}
  />

  <p>
    For questions about the lab specifically, the best resource is always a senior lab
    member or your co-supervisor. Don't hesitate to ask — everyone started where you are.
  </p>

</DocsLayout>
